have written is the final word.

00:06:45.520 --> 00:06:48.440
I think this is an
ongoing conversation

00:06:48.440 --> 00:06:51.450
that we are having
and are involved in.

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:55.030
I'm hoping that our knowledge
is being deepened by the work

00:06:55.030 --> 00:06:59.120
that we are producing both for
academic audiences but also

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:01.870
for popular audiences
and the readers

00:07:01.870 --> 00:07:04.910
of publications like
<i>Slate Magazine </i>.

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:10.270
Today, there's approximately
one million Americans

00:07:10.270 --> 00:07:13.190
who self-identify as Cherokee.

00:07:13.190 --> 00:07:18.660 position:56%
That is people who believe that they
have a Cherokee ancestor somewhere

00:07:18.660 --> 00:07:20.030
in their genealogy.

00:07:20.030 --> 00:07:24.130
That's become an important article
of an individual's identity,

00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:28.940
it seems, in the late 20th
and early 21st century.

00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:32.490
And this explosion -- for
one of the better expression,

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:35.790
in people who claim
Cherokee ancestry,

00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:37.850
begins in its modern formation

00:07:37.850 --> 00:07:42.300
around the late 1960s
and early 1970s.

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:47.630
And it seems to have become
mainstream during the early 1970s

00:07:47.630 --> 00:07:51.430
and it coincides with a
public service announcement

00:07:51.430 --> 00:07:55.250
that featured the gentleman
you see there on the screen.

00:07:55.250 --> 00:07:58.860
He's -- his stage name
was Iron Eyes Cody.

00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:02.230
Some of you are no doubt old
enough to remember that commercial

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:06.290
and his work in Hollywood,
in film and on television.

00:08:06.290 --> 00:08:11.170
Iron Eyes Cody was the child

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:15.170
of Sicilian immigrants,
born in New Orleans.

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:20.060
He appropriated an identity
for himself as a Cherokee man

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:25.790
and he became quite a
successful actor in his own right.

00:08:25.790 --> 00:08:30.540
If you ask his descendants, his son
and grandchildren, they will insist

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:34.190
that Iron Eyes Cody
was indeed Cherokee.

00:08:34.190 --> 00:08:40.610 position:56%
Now the evidence is contrary to that
but the question remains, well why?

00:08:40.610 --> 00:08:44.720
Why were there so many people like
Iron Eyes Cody who appropriated

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:51.190
such an identity in the late 20th
century -- from the 1970s forward?

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:56.520
Part of the answer to
that is directly related

00:08:56.520 --> 00:09:00.210
to what some historians
and sociologists refer

00:09:00.210 --> 00:09:04.030
to as the ethnic revival movement.

00:09:04.030 --> 00:09:07.430
Ethnic revivals begin in the 1970s

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:12.760
and what they basically entail
are Americans rediscovering

00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:18.060
and reconnecting with their
ancestry -- their ethnic ancestry.

00:09:18.060 --> 00:09:23.140
This is also the era one must
keep in mind of multiculturalism.

00:09:23.140 --> 00:09:26.190
The Western world is
embracing ideals

00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:30.660
around multiculturalism
in the 1970s and 1980s.

00:09:30.660 --> 00:09:35.970
And it's during this era then when
people discover that they're Irish,

00:09:35.970 --> 00:09:40.990
that they're German, that they're
Hungarian, that they're Italian,

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:42.980
and that they're Native American.

00:09:42.980 --> 00:09:45.620
That these identities -- excuse me,

00:09:45.620 --> 00:09:49.770
begin to proliferate
throughout American culture.

00:09:49.770 --> 00:09:53.360
Part of this is a cynical attempt,

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:59.350
as the historian Matthew Frye
Jacobson has pointed out to try

00:09:59.350 --> 00:10:03.950
and mitigate the impact of racial
tension that existed in 1960s

00:10:03.950 --> 00:10:09.370
and 1970s America to try and
flatten out racial experiences.

00:10:09.370 --> 00:10:15.160
That we are all immigrants and
that in some way, racial suffering

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:20.550
and racial experiences have a
degree of equivalency about them.

00:10:20.550 --> 00:10:22.640
And that's -- that is,
indeed, misleading.

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:24.950
And I can go into more
details about that.

00:10:24.950 --> 00:10:29.730
But that gives you some
sense in the modern context

00:10:29.730 --> 00:10:32.440
of where this proliferation

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:37.040
in people claiming Cherokee
identity comes from.

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:41.940
Navajo was, at one point, the
most popular identity for people

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:46.120
to self-identify with in the
United States in the 1950s and '60s

00:10:46.120 --> 00:10:50.220
and that's largely a product
of Hollywood filmmaking.

00:10:50.220 --> 00:10:53.700
Thank you, John Wayne.

00:10:53.700 --> 00:10:59.430
But Cherokee becomes the identity
of choice and it still is today

00:10:59.430 --> 00:11:04.170
for people who insist that
they have Cherokee ancestors.

00:11:04.170 --> 00:11:08.790
So I'm going to come back to this
question then and take a detour

00:11:08.790 --> 00:11:11.740
through some of the
major points that I talk

00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:15.530
about in <i>The Cherokee Diaspora</i>
because it's in that book

00:11:15.530 --> 00:11:18.120
that I wanted to understand
this modern phenomenon.

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:24.610
<i>The Cherokee Diaspora </i>is really
a book about origins and becoming.

00:11:24.610 --> 00:11:30.920
It's a story that places
history and heritage in conflict.

00:11:30.920 --> 00:11:37.920 position:56%
Heritage is that phenomenon scholars
point out of creating meaning.

00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:42.680
And that's what many Americans have
been doing not only since the 1970s

00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:44.990
but for quite some time,
almost from the beginning --

00:11:44.990 --> 00:11:49.160
indeed, from the beginning of
our republic trying to create

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:52.090 position:56%
and cultivate some sense of meaning.

00:11:52.090 --> 00:11:59.340
Historians sometimes in a rather
snobbish fashion are dismissive

00:11:59.340 --> 00:12:01.470
of the heritage industry.

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:06.310
We trade in evidence we
like to convince ourselves.

00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:09.170
We get at the facts of the past.

00:12:09.170 --> 00:12:13.520
But as I like to remind my
students, all facts are mediated.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:17.510
They don't understand what I'm
talking about but by the end

00:12:17.510 --> 00:12:20.150 position:56%
of 16 weeks, they get it [laughter].

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:22.550
I nail it into them.

00:12:22.550 --> 00:12:24.190 position:56%
So who are the Cherokee people then?

00:12:24.190 --> 00:12:27.420 position:56%
Let me give you a brief
introduction to the Cherokee people,

00:12:27.420 --> 00:12:33.050
their culture which I have devoted
my career and adult life to.

00:12:33.050 --> 00:12:38.010
The Cherokee are an
Iroquoian-speaking people descended

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:44.220
possibly from migratory people
from the Northern Great Lakes.

00:12:44.220 --> 00:12:48.630
And they migrated southward
and settled in and claimed

00:12:48.630 --> 00:12:54.020
as their hunting territory
parts of what is today Virginia,

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:58.990
West Virginia, North and
South Carolina, Georgia,

00:12:58.990 --> 00:13:05.190
Alabama, Tennessee, and Kentucky.

00:13:05.190 --> 00:13:09.010
The linguistic and ethnic heritage
that the Cherokee brought with them

00:13:09.010 --> 00:13:12.830
to help them found their
communities in the --

00:13:12.830 --> 00:13:16.390
that were thriving by the time
the Spanish encountered them

00:13:16.390 --> 00:13:20.300
in the 16th century,
carried with them the legacy

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:24.400
of their Northern Great
Lakes heritage.

00:13:24.400 --> 00:13:29.760
Iroquoian etymology is evident
in a number of the town names

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:32.500
in Cherokee country
in the southeast.

00:13:32.500 --> 00:13:39.350
Towns such as Seneca and
Kituwa underscore those links.

00:13:39.350 --> 00:13:43.930
Most archaeologists believe that
the Cherokee people have been

00:13:43.930 --> 00:13:49.060 position:56%
in the southeast, in the Appalachian
Mountain region of the southeast

00:13:49.060 --> 00:13:52.490
for at least 4000 years,
if not longer.

00:13:52.490 --> 00:13:56.420
And the archaeological evidence
is dynamic and constantly changing

00:13:56.420 --> 00:14:00.950
so that we're always
reevaluating that chronology.

00:14:00.950 --> 00:14:07.040
By about 1000, the Cherokee
understood themselves to be

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:15.080
"the principal people", the Tsalagi
became politically identifiable

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:19.450
as town and clan communities
throughout the southeast.

00:14:19.450 --> 00:14:24.660
And as I mentioned, when De Soto
and his Spanish entrada moved

00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:29.500
through the south from
modern-day Florida all the way

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:33.330
through the mountain south and
interior south during the period

00:14:33.330 --> 00:14:39.710
between 1539 and 1542, they
encountered wonderfully dynamic,

00:14:39.710 --> 00:14:44.680
sophisticated and I should point
out, interconnected societies.

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:51.140
Societies that had long engaged
in trade, diplomacy, marriage.

00:14:51.140 --> 00:14:54.310
Most Native People in the
southeast practiced exogamous

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:55.610
marriage practices.

00:14:55.610 --> 00:14:59.540
That is they married
outside of their clan groups.

00:14:59.540 --> 00:15:03.450
These were incredibly rich
and sophisticated societies

00:15:03.450 --> 00:15:05.090
that the Spanish encountered.

00:15:05.090 --> 00:15:08.150
Above all, it's important to note

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:11.210
that the Cherokee people
lived in towns.

00:15:11.210 --> 00:15:13.230
Their identities were
centered on towns, in fact,

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:15.710
by the 17th and 18th century.

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:20.310
The Cherokee people, many
schoolchildren come to my classes.

00:15:20.310 --> 00:15:23.810
By the time they get to college and
they have some rough understanding

00:15:23.810 --> 00:15:28.410
that Cherokee people
belong to matrilineal clans.

00:15:28.410 --> 00:15:32.610
And that is absolutely true, seven
matrilineal clans connect people

00:15:32.610 --> 00:15:36.510
from the different towns in
the 17th and 18th century.

00:15:36.510 --> 00:15:42.140
But on a day-to-day basis, if you
were to meet your average Cherokee,

00:15:42.140 --> 00:15:44.900
say on the upper trading
path that ran

00:15:44.900 --> 00:15:49.330
through the Overhill Cherokee
towns in modern-day Tennessee,

00:15:49.330 --> 00:15:52.250
you would encounter people
who would identify their name

00:15:52.250 --> 00:15:54.280
and which town they were from.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:57.470
Which gives you a sense of what was
most important to their identity

00:15:57.470 --> 00:16:00.950
as Cherokee people in the
17th and 18th century.

00:16:00.950 --> 00:16:08.930
It was a connection to place and
ecology, the ecology of a region

00:16:08.930 --> 00:16:15.520
and an ecology that connected
one's town to a region as well.

00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:20.570
And this is what makes the
removal of Cherokee people

00:16:20.570 --> 00:16:24.640
in the early 19th century
so traumatic.

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:30.880
Because this is literally a ripping
of people from a sense of place

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:37.470
that leads to a discombobulation in
one's mental compass of the world

00:16:37.470 --> 00:16:40.620
and their sense of community.

00:16:40.620 --> 00:16:44.490
And above all, community was hugely
important to Cherokee people.

00:16:44.490 --> 00:16:48.030
These are people who
nurtured reciprocal cultures

00:16:48.030 --> 00:16:52.270
for many hundreds and thousands
of years in the southeast.

00:16:52.270 --> 00:16:56.220
At the same time, as
I detail in the book,

00:16:56.220 --> 00:17:00.960
the Cherokee people also
nurture migration stories.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:04.730
There are some wonderful migration
stories that the Cherokee relate

00:17:04.730 --> 00:17:08.780
to Europeans when they begin
to arrive in the interior south

00:17:08.780 --> 00:17:12.660
on a more regular basis in
the 17th and 18th centuries.

00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:14.100
Some of these stories talk

00:17:14.100 --> 00:17:18.740
about Cherokee ancestors crossing
a great bridge that later sank

00:17:18.740 --> 00:17:21.110
to the bottom of the ocean.

00:17:21.110 --> 00:17:26.750
Others talk about Cherokee
ancestors, the Ani-kutani,

00:17:26.750 --> 00:17:32.990
a group of priests -- seven
priests who allegedly migrated

00:17:32.990 --> 00:17:35.790
from a mythical island in the
middle of the Atlantic Ocean

00:17:35.790 --> 00:17:40.740
and ultimately settled and helped
to establish the seven mother towns

00:17:40.740 --> 00:17:43.760
in Cherokee country
in the southeast.

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:47.920
And there are other stories too,
of movement and resettlements,

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:52.450 position:56%
about stories of Cherokees migrating
to the darkening lands, that is,

00:17:52.450 --> 00:17:55.280 position:56%
lands west of the Mississippi River.

00:17:55.280 --> 00:18:00.100
And some, the so-called Lost
Cherokee, migrating to the base

00:18:00.100 --> 00:18:02.090
of the so-called Mexican
Mountains --

00:18:02.090 --> 00:18:07.430
you might all know them as the
Rockies -- and not returning.

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:12.680
So there are stories of
movements, resettlements that exist

00:18:12.680 --> 00:18:16.220
within Cherokee folklore
and mythology

00:18:16.220 --> 00:18:18.700
and Cherokee oral histories.

00:18:18.700 --> 00:18:22.440
And in some ways, I think
that these histories are part,

00:18:22.440 --> 00:18:25.940 position:56%
though part of the way to explaining
why there are so many people

00:18:25.940 --> 00:18:31.820 position:56%
in the United States, Canada,
Mexico, and other parts of the world

00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:36.250
who believe that there are
connections to a Cherokee ancestry.

00:18:36.250 --> 00:18:42.080
Cherokee people have
long been mobile.

00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:45.070
They have been willing
to adopt outsiders

00:18:45.070 --> 00:18:47.710 position:56%
into their communities and families.

00:18:47.710 --> 00:18:50.440
So it comes as very little
surprise then that there would be

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:54.550
so many people who have these vague
stories that have become vaguer

00:18:54.550 --> 00:18:58.700
over time that connect
them to some sense

00:18:58.700 --> 00:19:01.970
of Cherokee-ness or
Cherokee identity.

00:19:06.290 --> 00:19:11.210
On the screen there, what you see
is a reproduction or a recreation,

00:19:11.210 --> 00:19:14.050
I should say, of a
typical Cherokee town

00:19:14.050 --> 00:19:17.740
that Europeans would have
encountered on a regular basis

00:19:17.740 --> 00:19:19.890
in the 17th and 18th century.

00:19:19.890 --> 00:19:24.730
This is a town where one's identity
would have been totally consumed

00:19:24.730 --> 00:19:29.910
by the day-to-day operations
of agricultural production,

00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:37.410 position:56%
of cultural engagements, of
educating children which was the job

00:19:37.410 --> 00:19:42.790
of the women of the town and
the uncles of the children.

00:19:42.790 --> 00:19:46.930
Fathers had very little
to do with their children

00:19:46.930 --> 00:19:50.940
in most Native Southern societies
during the 17th and 18th century.

00:19:50.940 --> 00:19:55.700
And that's a product of these
being matrilineal societies.

00:19:57.190 --> 00:20:01.420
Cherokee people began
to move their towns

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:03.620
over the course of
early 18th century.

00:20:03.620 --> 00:20:06.860
Certainly after the major schism

00:20:06.860 --> 00:20:10.780
that occurred throughout the Native
South that led some societies

00:20:10.780 --> 00:20:15.560
to reform after the
Yamasee War, a major battle

00:20:15.560 --> 00:20:25.590
that took place very near the Lower
Creek towns in 1715 through '18.

00:20:25.590 --> 00:20:26.890
This had an impact.

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:30.880
This war had an impact on
all of the Native South.

00:20:30.880 --> 00:20:33.880
For the Cherokee people, this war

00:20:33.880 --> 00:20:38.410
in the early18th century was
the beginning of sustained

00:20:38.410 --> 00:20:42.230
and almost daily contact
with the British.

00:20:42.230 --> 00:20:47.470
The British coveted the Tennessee
River, the little Tennessee

00:20:47.470 --> 00:20:50.800
and the other navigable rivers
that ran through Cherokee country

00:20:50.800 --> 00:20:56.280
as highways of the 18th century
that would provide them with access

00:20:56.280 --> 00:21:02.800
to the Ohio and Illinois Valleys
to connect plantations and markets

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:05.550
and make settlement possible.

00:21:05.550 --> 00:21:10.690
The problem was that chiefs
like John Jolly who you see

00:21:10.690 --> 00:21:13.840
on the screen there, they
controlled the Native South.

00:21:13.840 --> 00:21:17.160
This was Native country.

00:21:17.160 --> 00:21:19.870
And it's really not until
the late 18th century

00:21:19.870 --> 00:21:25.830 position:56%
that the British are able to acquire
the type of control that they hoped

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:30.740
for and indeed the ultimate
control over the Native South.

00:21:30.740 --> 00:21:36.840
It really doesn't come until the
Removal Era in the 1820s and 1830s.

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:43.760
It requires effort to remove over
70,000 Native Americans from East

00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:49.800 position:56%
to North America before Anglo-Saxon
people can dominate the Native South

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:52.830
and the Ohio and Illinois Valleys.

00:21:52.830 --> 00:21:56.210
Now for many Cherokee
people like Chief Jolly,

00:21:56.210 --> 00:22:00.960
who you see on the screen there,
they begin to grow despondent

00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:05.560
and resentful of the
aggressive of Europeans.

00:22:05.560 --> 00:22:08.210
And they begin to relocate
their towns.

00:22:08.210 --> 00:22:14.090
They begin to do that firstly by
relocating towns to the interior

00:22:14.090 --> 00:22:18.020 position:56%
of Cherokee country which goes a
long way to explaining why there are

00:22:18.020 --> 00:22:22.740
so many Cherokees removed
from Georgia in 1838 and '39.

00:22:22.740 --> 00:22:26.690
They had been taking refuge
in what becomes the colony

00:22:26.690 --> 00:22:28.900
and ultimately state of Georgia

00:22:28.900 --> 00:22:31.900
since the middle of
the 18th century.

00:22:31.900 --> 00:22:34.490
That's not enough for some people.

00:22:34.490 --> 00:22:39.850
Certainly, it's not for
John Jolly and his followers

00:22:39.850 --> 00:22:45.130
who become what I refer to in <i>The
Cherokee Diaspora </i>as the vanguard

00:22:45.130 --> 00:22:46.880
of diasporic communities.

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:52.150
They migrate to Arkansas
Territory and they migrate not

00:22:52.150 --> 00:23:00.000 position:56%
as they had once done as men engaged
in hunting and slave-raiding.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:04.150
They migrated as entire communities

00:23:04.150 --> 00:23:07.690
with relatively balanced
gender ratios.

00:23:07.690 --> 00:23:12.490
This is something that is entirely
new in modern Cherokee history

00:23:12.490 --> 00:23:16.190
than at the beginning
of the 19th century.

00:23:16.190 --> 00:23:22.810
By way of party knowledge perhaps,
Chief John Jolly is the man

00:23:22.810 --> 00:23:27.350
who adopts Sam Houston as his son.

00:23:27.350 --> 00:23:31.260
And indeed, when Sam Houston's wife
leaves him while Sam Houston is

00:23:31.260 --> 00:23:36.720
governor of Tennessee, Mr.
Houston has a mental breakdown

00:23:36.720 --> 00:23:43.280
and seeks refuge and comfort from
his adoptive father, Chief Jolly,

00:23:43.280 --> 00:23:49.940
and indeed migrates with the "old
settlers" to Arkansas Territory.

00:23:49.940 --> 00:23:52.750
The movement of Cherokee
people west then begins

00:23:52.750 --> 00:23:54.860
to really accelerate
during the first couple

00:23:54.860 --> 00:23:56.850
of decades of the 19th century.

00:23:56.850 --> 00:23:59.120
The man you see on the
screen there and I'm not sure

00:23:59.120 --> 00:24:01.500
if there's a picture of him.

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:02.800
This image is from the Library

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:04.900
of Congress collections,
I should point out.

00:24:04.900 --> 00:24:10.430 position:56%
And in fact, most of the images from
the book do come from the Library

00:24:10.430 --> 00:24:12.420
of Congress' collections.

00:24:12.420 --> 00:24:16.940
This is Tahchee or Dutch.

00:24:16.940 --> 00:24:20.210
He becomes -- he's a
great warrior chief

00:24:20.210 --> 00:24:25.050
and historians have written much
about his knife and various poses

00:24:25.050 --> 00:24:28.540
that he has throughout
his adult life,

00:24:28.540 --> 00:24:32.520
prominently displaying his knife

00:24:32.520 --> 00:24:37.410
to the artist making
the rendering of him.

00:24:37.410 --> 00:24:41.770
He is -- he's a celebrated
war chief among the Cherokees

00:24:41.770 --> 00:24:45.630
and he leads a group of
Cherokees into Arkansas Territory

00:24:45.630 --> 00:24:48.760
and ultimately into Texas.

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:50.140
What's interesting about Dutch --

00:24:50.140 --> 00:24:52.770
and I go into much more detail
about Dutch in the book,

00:24:52.770 --> 00:24:57.380 position:56%
but what's interesting about Dutch's
followers is many of them break off

00:24:57.380 --> 00:25:04.680
and settle in Northern
Mexico during the 1830s.

00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:09.120
This is as a result of the Texas
effort to remove Native Americans

00:25:09.120 --> 00:25:12.990
from the Republic of Texas.

00:25:12.990 --> 00:25:16.200
Others try to stay in
Texas and assimilate

00:25:16.200 --> 00:25:21.800
into white settler communities
or join Comanche communities

00:25:21.800 --> 00:25:26.400
who continue to terrorize
Anglo-Texan communities well

00:25:26.400 --> 00:25:28.590
into the 19th century.

00:25:28.590 --> 00:25:35.270
And others ultimately of Dutch's
followers are relocated in 1837,

00:25:35.270 --> 00:25:37.960
'38 into Indian Territory.

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:41.700 position:56%
One of the more interesting things
about Dutch's followers is that some

00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:45.250
of them seem to exist
as small communities,

00:25:45.250 --> 00:25:48.820
very small communities isolated
from both settler communities

00:25:48.820 --> 00:25:52.230
and other native communities
that are indigenous to Texas

00:25:52.230 --> 00:25:56.110
and its Cherokee search
parties that find them.

00:25:56.110 --> 00:26:00.780 position:56%
Chief Ross, when he's reestablishing
government in Indian Territory

00:26:00.780 --> 00:26:05.170
after the Removal crisis, sends
out Cherokee search parties to look

00:26:05.170 --> 00:26:09.710
for lost Cherokees and they're
often delighted to discover

00:26:09.710 --> 00:26:11.970
that there are people
who speak their language

00:26:11.970 --> 00:26:15.970
and they can be reconnected
with a sense of community again.

00:26:15.970 --> 00:26:18.500
And this is very important.

00:26:18.500 --> 00:26:23.890
This sense of community remains
important through the 19th century

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:25.980
through the trauma of Removal.

00:26:25.980 --> 00:26:30.700
And I should point out
something about Removal.

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:40.580
It is an effort that embodies
the exploitation of peoples,

00:26:40.580 --> 00:26:45.880
the expropriation of their
lands, and the use of technology.

00:26:45.880 --> 00:26:53.790
Railroads, steam boats, and so
forth to relocate tens of thousands

00:26:53.790 --> 00:26:58.630 position:56%
of people from land that southerners
covet for their slave plantations.

00:26:58.630 --> 00:27:04.320
And so in the midst of all of
this, how does one maintain a sense

00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:08.410
of community which is so
important to being Cherokee?

00:27:08.410 --> 00:27:12.510
Part of the answer to that
resides with people like Sequoyah

00:27:12.510 --> 00:27:14.970
who you see on the screen there.

00:27:14.970 --> 00:27:17.270
Sequoyah is the man
who is responsible

00:27:17.270 --> 00:27:22.120
for inventing the Cherokee
syllabary, a phonetic system

00:27:22.120 --> 00:27:27.850
of writing that does catch fire
among Cherokee people during the

00:27:27.850 --> 00:27:29.880
early 19th century.

00:27:29.880 --> 00:27:35.470
Sequoyah is -- Sequoyah
makes quite a deal

00:27:35.470 --> 00:27:39.290
of money actually selling jewelry

00:27:39.290 --> 00:27:42.440
that he manufactures during his
adult like and he's something

00:27:42.440 --> 00:27:47.120
of a cattle rancher for a period
as well during his early life.

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:51.260
He has links to some of the great
Cherokee chiefs of the late 18th

00:27:51.260 --> 00:27:55.270
and early 19th century such
as Tahlonteeskee who I write

00:27:55.270 --> 00:27:57.240
about in great length in the book.

00:27:57.240 --> 00:28:01.030
Tahlonteeskee is one of those
chiefs who leads the vanguard

00:28:01.030 --> 00:28:04.640
of Cherokee settlements
in the early 19th century.

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:10.980
So in other words, Sequoyah grows
up, certainly not impoverished

00:28:10.980 --> 00:28:14.680
but certainly not willing
to be passive in the face

00:28:14.680 --> 00:28:16.990
of settler encroachment
upon their lands

00:28:16.990 --> 00:28:20.480
and settler cultural imperialism.

00:28:20.480 --> 00:28:27.120
And so he sees -- the story
goes in his adult life,

00:28:27.120 --> 00:28:31.630
Cherokee people being intimidated
by European Americans being able

00:28:31.630 --> 00:28:35.110
to speak without talking.

00:28:35.110 --> 00:28:41.970
"There's nothing special in
that," Sequoyah allegedly says.

00:28:41.970 --> 00:28:47.250
And so he sets about trying to
come up with a system of writing

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:52.170
that can connect Cherokee
people, to enable Cherokee people

00:28:52.170 --> 00:28:53.910
to speak without talking.

00:28:53.910 --> 00:28:58.400
Now, sure but now the Cherokees
think he's absolutely nuts

00:28:58.400 --> 00:29:00.380
when he's doing this.

00:29:00.380 --> 00:29:04.790
But as I say, it does catch fire
very quickly and you do have

00:29:04.790 --> 00:29:08.290
as over here, you can see
after the talk an example.

00:29:08.290 --> 00:29:11.710
One of the great examples
of bilingualism

00:29:11.710 --> 00:29:15.310
in early 19th century
America, the Cherokee Phoenix

00:29:15.310 --> 00:29:20.280
which in many ways is a product
of Sequoyah's fabulous invention

00:29:20.280 --> 00:29:22.980 position:56%
and the hard work of Elias Boudinot,

00:29:22.980 --> 00:29:26.520
the first great editor
of the Cherokee Phoenix.

00:29:26.520 --> 00:29:33.580 position:56%
Who also plays a significant role
in using language and culture to try

00:29:33.580 --> 00:29:37.520
and connect people over vast
distances in this new reality

00:29:37.520 --> 00:29:44.580
that is Cherokee life in an
American imperial context.

00:29:44.580 --> 00:29:51.720
So it is then by the 1830s
in that awful era of Removal

00:29:51.720 --> 00:29:55.770
that separates families --
Cherokee families that leads

00:29:55.770 --> 00:29:59.640
to great suffering on the part
of Cherokee communities --

00:29:59.640 --> 00:30:04.430
that creates two separate
homelands for the Cherokee people.

00:30:04.430 --> 00:30:10.690
One that the Cherokees have to
recreate for themselves in diaspora

00:30:10.690 --> 00:30:13.300
in Indian Territory,
which is located

00:30:13.300 --> 00:30:16.580
in modern-day Eastern Oklahoma.

00:30:16.580 --> 00:30:18.500
This becomes a political homeland

00:30:18.500 --> 00:30:23.170
for Cherokee peoples living
throughout the Americas and beyond.

00:30:23.170 --> 00:30:25.170
But what gives that homeland --

00:30:25.170 --> 00:30:29.470 position:56%
that political homeland its enduring
meaning during the 19th century

00:30:29.470 --> 00:30:34.130
and into the 20th century is the
recognition that there are some

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:38.560
of our ancestors the Cherokees
note in their writings,

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:41.810
in their lectures and so forth.

00:30:41.810 --> 00:30:46.800 position:56%
Cherokees who remain in North
Carolina, in the ancestral homelands

00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:50.810
and it's very important then that
these political and western --

00:30:50.810 --> 00:30:56.740
political homeland remain
connected to the ancestral homeland

00:30:56.740 --> 00:30:58.820
of the Appalachian region.

00:30:58.820 --> 00:31:00.520
And we do see and I talked --

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:03.830
I write about this in
great length in the book.

00:31:03.830 --> 00:31:06.500
Cherokee people coming,
traveling back and forth

00:31:06.500 --> 00:31:11.230
on a regular basis during the
19th century and the 20th century

00:31:11.230 --> 00:31:16.050
to remain to try and cultivate
a renewed sense of community.

00:31:16.050 --> 00:31:22.150
And it is quite possible within the
context of that movement of people

00:31:22.150 --> 00:31:26.010
that new relationships are
forged with non-Cherokee people

00:31:26.010 --> 00:31:30.230
that give rise to these family
stories that I hear so often

00:31:30.230 --> 00:31:32.010
in my classes from my students.

00:31:32.010 --> 00:31:37.820
I should point out also at
this point that in the decades

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:44.340
between the 1830s and the outbreak
of the American Civil War in 1861,

00:31:44.340 --> 00:31:49.230
there is a phenomenon
sweeping across the Old South.

00:31:49.230 --> 00:31:52.800
It is the phenomenon
of white men claiming

00:31:52.800 --> 00:31:56.820
that they have Cherokee
grandmothers.

00:31:57.950 --> 00:32:00.210
This is not a phenomenon.

00:32:00.210 --> 00:32:07.810
Why? Why did this catch fire
in the Antebellum Decades?

00:32:07.810 --> 00:32:11.450
Well part of the answer
goes to the idea

00:32:11.450 --> 00:32:15.550
that American colonialism
had successfully in the minds

00:32:15.550 --> 00:32:19.240
of white Americans
removed all Cherokees

00:32:19.240 --> 00:32:21.950
from Eastern North America.

00:32:21.950 --> 00:32:24.540
And so by claiming
a Cherokee identity

00:32:24.540 --> 00:32:28.840
like claiming an Indian mascot,
you are engaging in a form

00:32:28.840 --> 00:32:32.150
of cultural appropriation
and cultural imperialism

00:32:32.150 --> 00:32:36.750
that denotes your -- in this
context racial, political,

00:32:36.750 --> 00:32:39.510
and military superiority.

00:32:39.510 --> 00:32:41.400
That's one aspect of this.

00:32:41.400 --> 00:32:46.400 position:56%
But the other aspect of this relates
to the growing tensions that emerge

00:32:46.400 --> 00:32:50.750
between North and South
during the Antebellum years,

00:32:50.750 --> 00:32:55.040
the 1830s through the 1850s.

00:32:55.040 --> 00:32:58.310
This growing suspicion that
there was this authoritarian,

00:32:58.310 --> 00:33:01.380
overreaching federal
government that was trying

00:33:01.380 --> 00:33:05.750
to impinge upon the rights
of Southerners were just

00:33:05.750 --> 00:33:09.540
like the Cherokees who were
removed by this overbearing,

00:33:09.540 --> 00:33:14.780
overreaching federal government
in the 1820s and 1830s.

00:33:14.780 --> 00:33:19.370
And so there's this
false sense of identity

00:33:19.370 --> 00:33:22.130
and misleading use of history.

00:33:22.130 --> 00:33:29.410
Indeed, I would say a cultivation
of a heritage here that goes part

00:33:29.410 --> 00:33:32.370
of the way to explaining
why you have this phenomenon

00:33:32.370 --> 00:33:34.090
in the Antebellum Decades.

00:33:34.090 --> 00:33:38.830
And it's this phenomenon and many
of the students that I've had here

00:33:38.830 --> 00:33:44.120
and oh, down in Virginia tell
me that their ancestors relate

00:33:44.120 --> 00:33:49.010
that it is during the early 19th
century that their relatives,

00:33:49.010 --> 00:33:55.030
they found letters in old suitcases
and so forth, of relatives talking

00:33:55.030 --> 00:33:58.620
about their Cherokee
ancestry during these decades.

00:33:58.620 --> 00:34:02.660
I think that is very revealing
about the cultural context then

00:34:02.660 --> 00:34:06.850
in which this belief
begins to emerge.

00:34:06.850 --> 00:34:13.080
At the same time -- at the same
time and I should say it's easy

00:34:13.080 --> 00:34:15.570
to be cynical about
some of this stuff.

00:34:15.570 --> 00:34:17.500
But at the same time that
all of this is happening,

00:34:17.500 --> 00:34:22.550
Cherokees continue to be
moving throughout the Americas.

00:34:22.550 --> 00:34:25.700
The image on the screen there is
an image of the California road

00:34:25.700 --> 00:34:31.730
that Cherokees regularly took
to California in search of gold?

00:34:31.730 --> 00:34:36.770
But some settled and of all the
satellite Cherokee communities

00:34:36.770 --> 00:34:41.070
in the United States today, the
satellite communities in Northern

00:34:41.070 --> 00:34:43.550
and Southern California
are among the most active.

00:34:43.550 --> 00:34:50.100
And many of them can trace their
ancestors back to Tennessee,

00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:55.710
Georgia, and the Old
Nation prior to Removal.

00:34:55.710 --> 00:34:59.430
Interestingly, this
California road didn't end

00:34:59.430 --> 00:35:01.420
when it got to California.

00:35:01.420 --> 00:35:06.630
Many Cherokees decided after they
didn't find gold in California

00:35:06.630 --> 00:35:12.070
that they would hop on a steamer
in San Francisco Bay and head

00:35:12.070 --> 00:35:18.030
to the antipodes, to
Australia, and try and find gold

00:35:18.030 --> 00:35:21.680
in the Victorian Gold Rush that
was occurring simultaneously.

00:35:21.680 --> 00:35:26.640
This was quite an extraordinary
transnational exchange

00:35:26.640 --> 00:35:29.050
of cultures that took place then.

00:35:29.050 --> 00:35:32.950
Many Cherokees returned
again impoverished

00:35:32.950 --> 00:35:35.030
from their efforts
to try and find gold.

00:35:35.030 --> 00:35:39.990
But there are examples
of Cherokees who did stay

00:35:39.990 --> 00:35:42.690
and intermarry in Australia.

00:35:42.690 --> 00:35:45.250 position:56%
And I've met many of those ancestors

00:35:45.250 --> 00:35:50.150
over the years while I've
been researching this book.

00:35:50.150 --> 00:35:56.880
The overarching memory that
dominates Cherokee stories

00:35:56.880 --> 00:36:00.910
of migration and resettlement
is what was called in the 1830s

00:36:00.910 --> 00:36:03.410
by the Cherokees, the
Great Immigration.

00:36:03.410 --> 00:36:05.850
I'm not going to tell
you how that term,

00:36:05.850 --> 00:36:07.410
the Trail of Tears came into being.

00:36:07.410 --> 00:36:10.900
You have to buy the book to
find that out [laughter].

00:36:10.900 --> 00:36:17.160 position:56%
But this was truly, as I mentioned,
an example of the use of technology,

00:36:17.160 --> 00:36:21.420
political power, military power.

00:36:21.420 --> 00:36:27.130 position:56%
And it's this migration, this forced
migration that dominates narratives

00:36:27.130 --> 00:36:32.630
of what it means to be Cherokee
going into the late 19th century.

00:36:32.630 --> 00:36:38.210
And it's really not until the era
of the Dawes Act and Allotment

00:36:38.210 --> 00:36:43.670 position:56%
that we begin to renew conversations
about what it means to be Cherokee.

00:36:43.670 --> 00:36:49.100
During that latter
period in the 1880s,

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:53.570
when the Dawes Commission is doing
its work and land is being allotted

00:36:53.570 --> 00:36:56.740
in Indian Territory,
what becomes Oklahoma --

00:36:56.740 --> 00:37:01.310
there are many Cherokee people
who refused to have anything

00:37:01.310 --> 00:37:03.360
to do with the commissioners.

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:11.370
They are both disdainful of and
distrustful of federal officials.

00:37:11.370 --> 00:37:12.670
And with good reason.

00:37:12.670 --> 00:37:14.660
They've heard the stories.

00:37:14.660 --> 00:37:18.540
There are many stories that
I collected from the 1920s --

00:37:18.540 --> 00:37:22.700
that date to the 1920s and
'30s which go a long way

00:37:22.700 --> 00:37:25.870
to explaining why many
Cherokee people would avoid

00:37:25.870 --> 00:37:27.280
federal officials.

00:37:27.280 --> 00:37:32.290
Now that has an enduring impact
upon Cherokee identity to this day.

00:37:32.290 --> 00:37:37.150
Because there are tens of thousands
possibly of Cherokee people,

00:37:37.150 --> 00:37:43.420
some of them working in academia,
who now have a very clear sense

00:37:43.420 --> 00:37:48.890 position:56%
of their Cherokee ancestors but they
do not appear on the Dawes Roll --

00:37:48.890 --> 00:37:53.150
that list of names that
determines one's connection

00:37:53.150 --> 00:37:56.010
to the Cherokee Nation
and eligibility

00:37:56.010 --> 00:37:58.170
into the Cherokee Nation.

00:37:58.170 --> 00:38:02.730
So this is really a
fraught period that's

00:38:02.730 --> 00:38:05.650
in some ways marks a
new beginning then.

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:10.060
If the Great Immigration of
the 1830s marked this sort

00:38:10.060 --> 00:38:15.340
of dramatic beginning for
Cherokee people's living en masse

00:38:15.340 --> 00:38:22.020
in diaspora, then a period of
relative stability certainly upset

00:38:22.020 --> 00:38:25.770
by the Civil War which I
talk more about in the book,

00:38:25.770 --> 00:38:30.190
is again unsettled and
new understandings emerge

00:38:30.190 --> 00:38:32.000
out of the Allotment Era.

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:35.970
And in many ways, the debates
about what it means to be Cherokee

00:38:35.970 --> 00:38:40.730
that emerged out of the 1880s
and 1890s are even more fraught

00:38:40.730 --> 00:38:44.050
and traumatic and really
quite visceral and violent

00:38:44.050 --> 00:38:47.510
in some cases during this era.

00:38:47.510 --> 00:38:53.110
This is also the era then
in the late 19th century

00:38:53.110 --> 00:38:57.460
where we do see a further
dispersal of Cherokee people.

00:38:57.460 --> 00:39:02.390
Cherokee people deciding that this
is no longer Indian Territory.

00:39:02.390 --> 00:39:06.660
Oklahoma is no longer a viable
option for their families.

00:39:06.660 --> 00:39:09.780
Many people choose
to live in diaspora.

00:39:09.780 --> 00:39:12.780
Narcissa Owen is one of those.

00:39:12.780 --> 00:39:15.080
She's well known in
Washington, DC at the turn

00:39:15.080 --> 00:39:18.190
of the 19th and 20th century.

00:39:18.190 --> 00:39:22.540
She marries a prominent railroad
engineer and lives for a period

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:27.150
in Lynchburg, Virginia and travels
back and forth during her life

00:39:27.150 --> 00:39:31.290
between the Cherokee
Seminary which is located

00:39:31.290 --> 00:39:35.110
in the Cherokee Nation
and Washington, DC.

00:39:35.110 --> 00:39:40.520
But Narcissa Owen is
in some ways fortunate.

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:44.010
She was able to put her
name on the Dawes Roll.

00:39:44.010 --> 00:39:48.120
She was able to prove beyond a
reasonable doubt her Cherokee

00:39:48.120 --> 00:39:51.850
ancestry at the end
of the 19th century.

00:39:51.850 --> 00:39:53.900
But many others were not.

00:39:53.900 --> 00:39:57.560
And I want to sort of
conclude by pointing

00:39:57.560 --> 00:40:01.090
to the Cherokee Citizenship
Commission which, to my mind,

00:40:01.090 --> 00:40:04.490
