Cherokees from poor white
settlers or white settlers, period.

00:51:31.390 --> 00:51:34.030
So that also, I think,

00:51:34.030 --> 00:51:39.050
goes to explaining the
nature of those images.

00:51:39.050 --> 00:51:44.600
&gt;&gt; I was just wondering when
you talked to your kids about --

00:51:44.600 --> 00:51:47.450
your students, I'm sorry,
not your kids [laughter].

00:51:47.450 --> 00:51:49.100
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers:
They are my children.

00:51:49.100 --> 00:51:51.000
&gt;&gt; What do you normally
[inaudible] about, you know,

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.790
how many of them identify
as Cherokee or how many --

00:51:53.790 --> 00:51:55.130
so you talked a lot about heritage

00:51:55.130 --> 00:51:58.080
but do you ever discuss the
differences between people

00:51:58.080 --> 00:52:01.170
who culturally identify as
Native American or Cherokee

00:52:01.170 --> 00:52:02.840
and the difference between
people who just say,

00:52:02.840 --> 00:52:04.140
"I have a great-grandmother."

00:52:04.140 --> 00:52:05.440
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers: That's a
wonderful question actually.

00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:06.740
Yeah, I do.

00:52:06.740 --> 00:52:08.040
We talk a lot about that.

00:52:08.040 --> 00:52:11.810
And for a lot of people, it's not
something that's really lived.

00:52:11.810 --> 00:52:13.860
It's something that's just there.

00:52:13.860 --> 00:52:18.540
You know, Granny or Great-Grandma
talks about it as you know,

00:52:18.540 --> 00:52:20.230
we have this Cherokee ancestors.

00:52:20.230 --> 00:52:24.280 position:56%
And it makes us kind of exotic is
the sense I get from these students.

00:52:24.280 --> 00:52:28.250
So there's not the sense
that they're living.

00:52:28.250 --> 00:52:32.140
They're not living at a
sense of Cherokee identity

00:52:32.140 --> 00:52:34.490
and this is very important
because experience

00:52:34.490 --> 00:52:38.310
and experiential knowledge is at
the core of traditional knowledge.

00:52:38.310 --> 00:52:42.810
So in that sense, what they're
actually articulating, I find,

00:52:42.810 --> 00:52:47.260
is a racialized sense
of indigeneity.

00:52:47.260 --> 00:52:51.630
That is to say, this sort of
"Well, I have X amount of blood

00:52:51.630 --> 00:52:57.460
that is Cherokee, or Creek,
or Choctaw and this makes me

00:52:57.460 --> 00:53:01.340
in some ways connected to
this larger Cherokee diaspora

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:04.600
or community of indigenous people."

00:53:04.600 --> 00:53:09.400
And it elides the sort of important
cultural and linguistic factors

00:53:09.400 --> 00:53:13.440
that we've been talking about and
sense of community that remains

00:53:13.440 --> 00:53:17.300
at the core of Cherokee
identities in the 21st century.

00:53:17.300 --> 00:53:22.520
So yeah, so at the bottom line is
my overarching sense of all this is

00:53:22.520 --> 00:53:25.460
that people have a very
superficial understanding

00:53:25.460 --> 00:53:28.780
of what Cherokee identity means
and when they do give voice to it,

00:53:28.780 --> 00:53:33.410
it's in this sort of very
racialized blood quantum sense.

00:53:35.110 --> 00:53:36.640
&gt;&gt; So I know [inaudible]
from Australia.

00:53:36.640 --> 00:53:39.960
I was wondering in your research,
did you find any similarities

00:53:39.960 --> 00:53:42.940
between Cherokee Nation
and the aboriginal tribes

00:53:42.940 --> 00:53:46.090 position:56%
in Australia in terms of oppression?

00:53:46.090 --> 00:53:47.890
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers:
Oh, yes [laughter].

00:53:47.890 --> 00:53:51.650
My goodness, we don't have
enough time to go into that.

00:53:51.650 --> 00:53:56.140
I've written about that and I have
a revised edition of a book coming

00:53:56.140 --> 00:53:59.520
up called <i>Science, Sexuality
and Race </i>which talks

00:53:59.520 --> 00:54:03.330
about that in great detail.

00:54:03.330 --> 00:54:05.090
Yeah, the parallels
are quite striking

00:54:05.090 --> 00:54:10.630
and I originally got my start in
studying Native American history

00:54:10.630 --> 00:54:14.850
as an undergraduate when I was
working as a research assistant

00:54:14.850 --> 00:54:17.690 position:56%
at ATSIC which is the Aboriginal and
Torres Strait Islander Commission.

00:54:17.690 --> 00:54:22.580
You see, I came of age in Australia
at a time when land rights,

00:54:22.580 --> 00:54:26.280
recognition of aboriginal
land rights was foremost

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:29.370
in everyone's political
consciousness.

00:54:29.370 --> 00:54:31.910
And as an undergraduate,
as a college student,

00:54:31.910 --> 00:54:36.250
I worked on researching, doing
the historical research for some

00:54:36.250 --> 00:54:40.670
of those legal briefings that were
being put together during the late

00:54:40.670 --> 00:54:43.380
'80s and early '90s.

00:54:43.380 --> 00:54:45.400
And it's at that moment
that I realized,

00:54:45.400 --> 00:54:47.510
well there must be a
broader context to this.

00:54:47.510 --> 00:54:48.810
And indeed there is.

00:54:48.810 --> 00:54:50.910
And it goes beyond
the United States.

00:54:50.910 --> 00:54:54.720
In fact, it touches every
set withcolonial nation state

00:54:54.720 --> 00:54:56.880
that there is today.

00:54:56.880 --> 00:55:01.910 position:56%
So yeah. So the parallels are really
quite striking of frontier violence,

00:55:01.910 --> 00:55:07.770
of the removal of people to
access their lands and resources,

00:55:07.770 --> 00:55:12.390 position:56%
the forced use of indigenous labor
which is not often something we talk

00:55:12.390 --> 00:55:18.210 position:56%
about but the British colonies could
not have been possible if it was not

00:55:18.210 --> 00:55:20.570
for the Indian slave
trade of the 17th century.

00:55:20.570 --> 00:55:26.810
And the selling of so many
thousands of unnamed "Indians"

00:55:26.810 --> 00:55:31.470
into slavery throughout the British
colonies and the Caribbean as well.

00:55:31.470 --> 00:55:36.150
So the connections then are
just quite extraordinary

00:55:36.150 --> 00:55:38.350
across both time and space.

00:55:38.350 --> 00:55:39.650
&gt;&gt; You [inaudible] --

00:55:39.650 --> 00:55:41.200
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much
for your presentation.

00:55:41.200 --> 00:55:42.500
Fascinating and really interesting.

00:55:42.500 --> 00:55:43.800
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers: Thank you.

00:55:43.800 --> 00:55:46.500
&gt;&gt; There was an earlier question
about the notion of when identity

00:55:46.500 --> 00:55:49.390
for Native Americans comes
sort of into a vogue or part

00:55:49.390 --> 00:55:53.590
of the vocabulary and I think '76
is perhaps as [inaudible] goes,

00:55:53.590 --> 00:55:57.210
'76 is perhaps a little
too late in the game.

00:55:57.210 --> 00:56:00.110
Unlike, you alluded to the Civil
Rights Movement, for instance,

00:56:00.110 --> 00:56:03.660
of 1960s and certainly you'd
want to take into account things

00:56:03.660 --> 00:56:06.320
like the occupation of Alcatraz
by Native American [inaudible].

00:56:06.320 --> 00:56:07.620
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers: Oh, I
absolutely agree with you.

00:56:07.620 --> 00:56:10.020
&gt;&gt; Yeah and of course, you have
AIM and the Second Wounded Knee,

00:56:10.020 --> 00:56:14.230
the massacres and, you know,
also for instance that 1968,

00:56:14.230 --> 00:56:18.460
you have the Poor People's Campaign
which brought together people

00:56:18.460 --> 00:56:21.490
from Native American communities
with African-Americans.

00:56:21.490 --> 00:56:25.280
And also Hispanic people to march
on Washington and actually set

00:56:25.280 --> 00:56:28.570
up a tent city which was the last
major thing that Dr. King did

00:56:28.570 --> 00:56:33.410
and was planning on
before he was assassinated.

00:56:33.410 --> 00:56:35.440
They still went ahead anyway.

00:56:35.440 --> 00:56:41.500
And then, you know, I was
in the southwest recently

00:56:41.500 --> 00:56:45.930
and identity becomes a
very interesting thing

00:56:45.930 --> 00:56:48.450
because you see the histories
of people who had to go serve

00:56:48.450 --> 00:56:51.970
in the war with the Navajo
Code Talker [inaudible].

00:56:51.970 --> 00:56:57.680
But there were other groups
from Native American --

00:56:57.680 --> 00:57:07.300
from Indian country who were also
recruited precisely to do the kind

00:57:07.300 --> 00:57:11.300
of work in the trenches
and do a lot of, you know,

00:57:11.300 --> 00:57:14.340
break codes [inaudible]
transmit secrets in languages.

00:57:14.340 --> 00:57:18.790
But yet, their polarization
came when they came back

00:57:18.790 --> 00:57:22.970
and were denied full
citizenship even though, you know,

00:57:22.970 --> 00:57:29.680
they had fought for the
country in World War II.

00:57:29.680 --> 00:57:30.980
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers: Right.

00:57:30.980 --> 00:57:33.780
&gt;&gt; So I think there is a -- it's
a moving target [inaudible].

00:57:33.780 --> 00:57:35.880
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers: Oh, I
absolutely agree with you.

00:57:35.880 --> 00:57:40.500
&gt;&gt; And then as you said, it's very
complex but it's something to think

00:57:40.500 --> 00:57:43.690
about because in all
these instances,

00:57:43.690 --> 00:57:49.690
identity is not just a claim
in the name of multiculturalism

00:57:49.690 --> 00:57:52.100
but it's a very political act.

00:57:52.100 --> 00:57:54.480
It's a violent political act.

00:57:54.480 --> 00:57:55.780
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers: Right, yeah.

00:57:55.780 --> 00:57:57.080
No, I agree.

00:57:57.080 --> 00:57:58.380
I agree. No, I completely agree
with everything you've said.

00:57:58.380 --> 00:58:01.880
For non-indigenous community
members though, I think,

00:58:01.880 --> 00:58:03.480
it's really this culmination
is, you know,

00:58:03.480 --> 00:58:05.710
the appropriation is
what I'm referring

00:58:05.710 --> 00:58:07.820
to in the late '60s and early '70s.

00:58:07.820 --> 00:58:10.520
But you're absolutely right
about that pre-history

00:58:10.520 --> 00:58:13.100
that you're talking about.

00:58:13.100 --> 00:58:18.260
A term that I don't
particularly like to use but yeah,

00:58:18.260 --> 00:58:22.170
Cherokee Code Talk, as
I should point out too

00:58:22.170 --> 00:58:23.830
and I mention this in the book.

00:58:23.830 --> 00:58:26.230
There were as many
Cherokee Code Talkers

00:58:26.230 --> 00:58:28.740
or Code Breakers during
the Second World War

00:58:28.740 --> 00:58:30.970
as there were Navajo
Code Breakers as well.

00:58:30.970 --> 00:58:34.160
So yeah, so this -- and during
the Second World War also,

00:58:34.160 --> 00:58:41.620
I should point out, that
Cherokee people living in places

00:58:41.620 --> 00:58:49.790
like Illinois and Ohio throughout
the east, in New England,

00:58:49.790 --> 00:58:53.650
in the Mid-Atlantic,
they were very clear

00:58:53.650 --> 00:58:56.480
when they enlisted, who they were.

00:58:56.480 --> 00:59:04.560
So yeah, this is absolutely a
political statement on their part

00:59:04.560 --> 00:59:08.170
but it's also just a statement
of their being as human beings.

00:59:08.170 --> 00:59:11.750
They did not want any -- a
single molecule of their identity

00:59:11.750 --> 00:59:16.750
as human beings to be taken
from them by bureaucracy,

00:59:16.750 --> 00:59:18.880
or popular culture, or so forth.

00:59:18.880 --> 00:59:23.490
So I think that those are
extraordinarily valid points

00:59:23.490 --> 00:59:24.790
you raised.

00:59:24.790 --> 00:59:26.090
&gt;&gt; Go ahead.

00:59:26.090 --> 00:59:27.500
&gt;&gt; Follow-up question.

00:59:27.500 --> 00:59:31.550
Were there among Cherokee people
the same set of circumstances

00:59:31.550 --> 00:59:33.580
that happened with the
Removal and the Indian Schools

00:59:33.580 --> 00:59:34.900
which their whole point was to
[inaudible] Native American kids?

00:59:34.900 --> 00:59:36.370
Is that -- is there a similar
thing going on with the Cherokee?

00:59:36.370 --> 00:59:37.670
&gt;&gt; Gregory Smithers: Yup, there is.

00:59:37.670 --> 00:59:38.970
Yeah and it lasts well into
the 20th century as well.

00:59:38.970 --> 00:59:40.270 position:56%
And again, this is one of the
tragic consequences of the Dawes Act

00:59:40.270 --> 00:59:41.570
and the Era of Allotment
more generally is

00:59:41.570 --> 00:59:43.000
that the federal government closes
down those educational institutions

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:44.710
that the Cherokee Nation had built
and cultivated since Removal.

00:59:44.710 --> 00:59:46.300
The Cherokee male and female
seminaries were the first advanced

00:59:46.300 --> 00:59:47.770
level educational institutions
west of the Mississippi.

00:59:47.770 --> 00:59:49.300
And they are closed down by the
federal government during the

00:59:49.300 --> 00:59:50.860
Allotment Era and this leads
to this sort of tragic era

00:59:50.860 --> 00:59:52.540
of dispersing children throughout
all corners of the United States

00:59:52.540 --> 00:59:53.840
and that is indeed
something that I talk

00:59:53.840 --> 00:59:55.140
about in the book at great length.

00:59:55.140 --> 00:59:56.440 position:56%
Because the consequences of it are
really quite tragic, because many --

00:59:56.440 --> 00:59:57.740
many children feel so ashamed
of their indigenous heritage

00:59:57.740 --> 00:59:59.040
that they go to great
lengths to try and hide it.

00:59:59.040 --> 01:00:00.340
So much so that some
of those children refer

01:00:00.340 --> 01:00:01.640
to themselves as Swiss.

01:00:01.640 --> 01:00:02.940
You know, adopt this sort of Aryan
identity in the early 20th century.

01:00:02.940 --> 01:00:04.330
So it's really quite sad
and tragic what happened.

